<subSubSection pageId="60" pageNumber="61" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="60.[189,310,1912,1938]" box="[189,310,1912,1938]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,1912,1938]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,1912,1938]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="60.[189,1398,1961,2025]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
Thallus short, stout. Perithecium flask-shaped with a well-distinguished and narrow neck. Trichogyne stump remaining as an outgrowth on the outer side of the perithecium (
<figureCitation box="[1022,1163,1998,2024]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="62.[189,232,1786,1812]" captionTargetBox="[200,1387,265,1748]" captionTargetId="figure-125@62.[200,1387,265,1748]" captionTargetPageId="62" captionText="Fig. 10. Euphoriomyces spp. A. E. magnicellulatus Santam. Paired mature thalli, with elongated cell of receptacle (*). – B–F. E. smicri Santam. sp. nov. B–C. Immature thalli showing antheridia (arrows), primary appendage (pa), primary septum (a), and uppermost receptacular axial cell (*). D. Mature thallus showing cells VII, probably m (m?) and trichogyne stump (ts). E. Detail of the perithecial apex from F, with trichogyne stump (ts). F. Mature thallus with a labelled perithecial initial (arrow). Scale bars: A = 50 µm; B–D, F = 20 µm; E = 10 µm. Photographs from slides ZMUC C-F-124132 (A), and ZMUC C-F-122821 (holotype) (B–F)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5828948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5828948/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Fig. 10D–E</figureCitation>
, ts).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
