<subSubSection pageId="61" pageNumber="62" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="61.[189,334,772,798]" box="[189,334,772,798]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,334,772,798]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,334,772,798]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="61.[189,1399,827,1117]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">
Thallus hyaline, except for the blackened foot and yellowish perithecium. Receptacle axis consisting of 6–10 superposed cells which are broader than long, those of the basal area being especially flattened. Basal cell of the receptacle (I) slightly longer than broad, obtriangular. Two to four of the lower cells of the receptacle remain undivided; cells above dividing at one or both sides into cells giving rise to perithecium, secondary appendages, or antheridia. The latter broad, short, stout, sessile, on any of the two sides of thallus, usually only well-distinguished on immature thalli (
<figureCitation box="[1023,1161,1047,1073]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="62.[189,232,1786,1812]" captionTargetBox="[200,1387,265,1748]" captionTargetId="figure-125@62.[200,1387,265,1748]" captionTargetPageId="62" captionText="Fig. 10. Euphoriomyces spp. A. E. magnicellulatus Santam. Paired mature thalli, with elongated cell of receptacle (*). – B–F. E. smicri Santam. sp. nov. B–C. Immature thalli showing antheridia (arrows), primary appendage (pa), primary septum (a), and uppermost receptacular axial cell (*). D. Mature thallus showing cells VII, probably m (m?) and trichogyne stump (ts). E. Detail of the perithecial apex from F, with trichogyne stump (ts). F. Mature thallus with a labelled perithecial initial (arrow). Scale bars: A = 50 µm; B–D, F = 20 µm; E = 10 µm. Photographs from slides ZMUC C-F-124132 (A), and ZMUC C-F-122821 (holotype) (B–F)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5828948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5828948/files/figure.png" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Fig. 10B–C</figureCitation>
, arrows). Secondary appendages (
<figureCitation box="[342,448,1090,1117]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="62.[189,232,1786,1812]" captionTargetBox="[200,1387,265,1748]" captionTargetId="figure-125@62.[200,1387,265,1748]" captionTargetPageId="62" captionText="Fig. 10. Euphoriomyces spp. A. E. magnicellulatus Santam. Paired mature thalli, with elongated cell of receptacle (*). – B–F. E. smicri Santam. sp. nov. B–C. Immature thalli showing antheridia (arrows), primary appendage (pa), primary septum (a), and uppermost receptacular axial cell (*). D. Mature thallus showing cells VII, probably m (m?) and trichogyne stump (ts). E. Detail of the perithecial apex from F, with trichogyne stump (ts). F. Mature thallus with a labelled perithecial initial (arrow). Scale bars: A = 50 µm; B–D, F = 20 µm; E = 10 µm. Photographs from slides ZMUC C-F-124132 (A), and ZMUC C-F-122821 (holotype) (B–F)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5828948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5828948/files/figure.png" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Fig. 10C</figureCitation>
, sa) similar to the primary appendage.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="61.[189,1398,1165,1279]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">
Primary appendage unbranched, continuing the main receptacle axis, consisting of up to eight elongated cells (
<figureCitation box="[259,400,1208,1235]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="62.[189,232,1786,1812]" captionTargetBox="[200,1387,265,1748]" captionTargetId="figure-125@62.[200,1387,265,1748]" captionTargetPageId="62" captionText="Fig. 10. Euphoriomyces spp. A. E. magnicellulatus Santam. Paired mature thalli, with elongated cell of receptacle (*). – B–F. E. smicri Santam. sp. nov. B–C. Immature thalli showing antheridia (arrows), primary appendage (pa), primary septum (a), and uppermost receptacular axial cell (*). D. Mature thallus showing cells VII, probably m (m?) and trichogyne stump (ts). E. Detail of the perithecial apex from F, with trichogyne stump (ts). F. Mature thallus with a labelled perithecial initial (arrow). Scale bars: A = 50 µm; B–D, F = 20 µm; E = 10 µm. Photographs from slides ZMUC C-F-124132 (A), and ZMUC C-F-122821 (holotype) (B–F)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5828948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5828948/files/figure.png" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Fig. 10B–C</figureCitation>
, pa). The uppermost receptacular axis cell longer than broad, forming a peduncle for the primary appendage (
<figureCitation box="[474,580,1252,1278]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="62.[189,232,1786,1812]" captionTargetBox="[200,1387,265,1748]" captionTargetId="figure-125@62.[200,1387,265,1748]" captionTargetPageId="62" captionText="Fig. 10. Euphoriomyces spp. A. E. magnicellulatus Santam. Paired mature thalli, with elongated cell of receptacle (*). – B–F. E. smicri Santam. sp. nov. B–C. Immature thalli showing antheridia (arrows), primary appendage (pa), primary septum (a), and uppermost receptacular axial cell (*). D. Mature thallus showing cells VII, probably m (m?) and trichogyne stump (ts). E. Detail of the perithecial apex from F, with trichogyne stump (ts). F. Mature thallus with a labelled perithecial initial (arrow). Scale bars: A = 50 µm; B–D, F = 20 µm; E = 10 µm. Photographs from slides ZMUC C-F-124132 (A), and ZMUC C-F-122821 (holotype) (B–F)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5828948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5828948/files/figure.png" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Fig. 10C</figureCitation>
, *). Primary septum constricted (
<figureCitation box="[970,1104,1252,1279]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="62.[189,232,1786,1812]" captionTargetBox="[200,1387,265,1748]" captionTargetId="figure-125@62.[200,1387,265,1748]" captionTargetPageId="62" captionText="Fig. 10. Euphoriomyces spp. A. E. magnicellulatus Santam. Paired mature thalli, with elongated cell of receptacle (*). – B–F. E. smicri Santam. sp. nov. B–C. Immature thalli showing antheridia (arrows), primary appendage (pa), primary septum (a), and uppermost receptacular axial cell (*). D. Mature thallus showing cells VII, probably m (m?) and trichogyne stump (ts). E. Detail of the perithecial apex from F, with trichogyne stump (ts). F. Mature thallus with a labelled perithecial initial (arrow). Scale bars: A = 50 µm; B–D, F = 20 µm; E = 10 µm. Photographs from slides ZMUC C-F-124132 (A), and ZMUC C-F-122821 (holotype) (B–F)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5828948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5828948/files/figure.png" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Fig. 10C, a</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="61.[189,1399,1326,1447]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">
Perithecium solitary (only one thallus shows a second perithecial initial; 
<figureCitation box="[1040,1141,1326,1353]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="62.[189,232,1786,1812]" captionTargetBox="[200,1387,265,1748]" captionTargetId="figure-125@62.[200,1387,265,1748]" captionTargetPageId="62" captionText="Fig. 10. Euphoriomyces spp. A. E. magnicellulatus Santam. Paired mature thalli, with elongated cell of receptacle (*). – B–F. E. smicri Santam. sp. nov. B–C. Immature thalli showing antheridia (arrows), primary appendage (pa), primary septum (a), and uppermost receptacular axial cell (*). D. Mature thallus showing cells VII, probably m (m?) and trichogyne stump (ts). E. Detail of the perithecial apex from F, with trichogyne stump (ts). F. Mature thallus with a labelled perithecial initial (arrow). Scale bars: A = 50 µm; B–D, F = 20 µm; E = 10 µm. Photographs from slides ZMUC C-F-124132 (A), and ZMUC C-F-122821 (holotype) (B–F)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5828948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5828948/files/figure.png" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Fig. 10F</figureCitation>
, arrow), flask-shaped, with a broad venter and a narrow, abruptly distinguished neck. Apex blunt to flat. Trichogyne stump apparent, resulting into an outgrowth around cell w 
<subScript attach="left" box="[790,799,1433,1447]" fontSize="6" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">4</subScript>
(
<figureCitation box="[815,955,1414,1440]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="62.[189,232,1786,1812]" captionTargetBox="[200,1387,265,1748]" captionTargetId="figure-125@62.[200,1387,265,1748]" captionTargetPageId="62" captionText="Fig. 10. Euphoriomyces spp. A. E. magnicellulatus Santam. Paired mature thalli, with elongated cell of receptacle (*). – B–F. E. smicri Santam. sp. nov. B–C. Immature thalli showing antheridia (arrows), primary appendage (pa), primary septum (a), and uppermost receptacular axial cell (*). D. Mature thallus showing cells VII, probably m (m?) and trichogyne stump (ts). E. Detail of the perithecial apex from F, with trichogyne stump (ts). F. Mature thallus with a labelled perithecial initial (arrow). Scale bars: A = 50 µm; B–D, F = 20 µm; E = 10 µm. Photographs from slides ZMUC C-F-124132 (A), and ZMUC C-F-122821 (holotype) (B–F)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5828948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5828948/files/figure.png" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Fig. 10D–E</figureCitation>
, ts).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="61.[189,1398,1488,1559]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Length from foot to apex of perithecium 70–95 µm. Perithecium 40–63 × 17–27 µm. Maximum length of primary appendage from primary septum (when undamaged) 121 µm.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="61.[189,1398,1606,1676]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Thalli were found on the elytra of the hosts. The hosts were sifted from semi-dry, mouldy and rotten straw with many mice-tracks on sun-exposed grazed meadow.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="61" pageNumber="62" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="61.[189,303,1724,1750]" box="[189,303,1724,1750]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,303,1724,1750]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,303,1724,1750]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="61.[189,1399,1779,2025]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">
This is the first species of the genus described on a member of 
<taxonomicName box="[961,1064,1779,1805]" class="Insecta" family="Ptiliidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Ptiliidae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fairmaire &amp; Laboulbene" baseAuthorityYear="1855" box="[1078,1289,1779,1806]" class="Insecta" family="Ptiliidae" genus="Smicrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="filicornis">
<emphasis box="[1078,1289,1779,1806]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Smicrus filicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a rarely collected beetle usually found in fermenting, warm compost piles. The fungus does not seem to be related to any other known species of the genus. Although the material is scarce, we have not been able to resist describing it, given its exceptional nature. Some of the perithecial basal cells are barely apparent (
<figureCitation box="[198,300,1954,1981]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="62.[189,232,1786,1812]" captionTargetBox="[200,1387,265,1748]" captionTargetId="figure-125@62.[200,1387,265,1748]" captionTargetPageId="62" captionText="Fig. 10. Euphoriomyces spp. A. E. magnicellulatus Santam. Paired mature thalli, with elongated cell of receptacle (*). – B–F. E. smicri Santam. sp. nov. B–C. Immature thalli showing antheridia (arrows), primary appendage (pa), primary septum (a), and uppermost receptacular axial cell (*). D. Mature thallus showing cells VII, probably m (m?) and trichogyne stump (ts). E. Detail of the perithecial apex from F, with trichogyne stump (ts). F. Mature thallus with a labelled perithecial initial (arrow). Scale bars: A = 50 µm; B–D, F = 20 µm; E = 10 µm. Photographs from slides ZMUC C-F-124132 (A), and ZMUC C-F-122821 (holotype) (B–F)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5828948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5828948/files/figure.png" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Fig. 10D</figureCitation>
) which does not quite fit the genus description. Nevertheless, receptacle and other characteristics are seamlessly those described for the genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
